 the Trojan shepherd swept into the sky by an amorous Jupiter; the fifty daughters of Danaus, ordered by their father to kill their husbands on their wedding night; and Virgil's original tale of a domesticated wild stag whose killing sparks a war between Trojans and Italians. These ekphrases incorporate major themes of the Aeneid, an enduring formative text of the Western tradition, and provide a rich variety of interpretive perspectives on the poem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAeneas (Legendary character) in literature. 0aDescription (Rhetoric)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aEkphrasis. 0aEpic poetry, LatinxHistory and criticism. 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300147070.jpg  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles